  <bp:ProteinReference rdf:ID="ProteinReference23">
    <bp:organism rdf:resource="#BioSource1" />
    <bp:name rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">UniProt:P25391 LAMA1</bp:name>
    <bp:name rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">LAMA1</bp:name>
    <bp:name rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">LAMA</bp:name>
    <bp:xref rdf:resource="#UnificationXref248" />
    <bp:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">FUNCTION Binding to cells via a high affinity receptor, laminin is thought to mediate the attachment, migration and organization of cells into tissues during embryonic development by interacting with other extracellular matrix components.SUBUNIT Laminin is a complex glycoprotein, consisting of three different polypeptide chains (alpha, beta, gamma), which are bound to each other by disulfide bonds into a cross-shaped molecule comprising one long and three short arms with globules at each end. Alpha-1 is a subunit of laminin-1 (laminin-111 or EHS laminin) and laminin-3 (laminin-121 or S-laminin).DOMAIN The alpha-helical domains I and II are thought to interact with other laminin chains to form a coiled coil structure.DOMAIN Domains VI, IV and G are globular.PTM Tyrosine phosphorylated by PKDCC/VLK.</bp:comment>
  </bp:ProteinReference>
