    <bp:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">FUNCTION Binding to cells via a high affinity receptor, laminin is thought to mediate the attachment, migration and organization of cells into tissues during embryonic development by interacting with other extracellular matrix components.SUBUNIT Laminin is a complex glycoprotein, consisting of three different polypeptide chains (alpha, beta, gamma), which are bound to each other by disulfide bonds into a cross-shaped molecule comprising one long and three short arms with globules at each end. Beta-2 is a subunit of laminin-3 (laminin-121 or S-laminin), laminin-4 (laminin-221 or S-merosin), laminin-7 (laminin-321 or KS-laminin), laminin-9 (laminin-421), laminin-11 (laminin-521), laminin-14 (laminin-423) and laminin-15 (laminin-523).DOMAIN The alpha-helical domains I and II are thought to interact with other laminin chains to form a coiled coil structure.DOMAIN Domains VI and IV are globular.</bp:comment>
